class Solution {
    public int longestSemiRepetitiveSubstring(String s) {
        int n = s.length();
        int maxLength = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int count = 0;
            for (int j = i; j < n - 1; j++) {
                if (s.charAt(j) == s.charAt(j + 1)) count++;
                if (count > 1) break;
                maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, j - i + 2);
            }
        }
        return maxLength;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^2)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates over the string using a sliding window approach, checking for semi-repetitive substrings and updating the maximum length found. It has a high efficiency due to its simplicity and low overhead. 
